questionRound.0.question.9.answer: The way this game was set up was that each player's low sum X/Y was flipped for the subsequent players.  | Ie: if X was the high for Green and Y was the low  the reverse would be the matter for the next player. The only player whose payout was not determined by the choices of those before him is the final one. Therefore there was no incentive nor disincentive to choose the lower numbers or try to guess the patterns.  |  | If all the players grasped the pattern of the game the payout could have been maximized for all because the final choice was guaranteed to be the high sum. Which is where things get tricky if one player chooses to continue picking high numbers in favor of the low ones  for one they will end up with smaller payouts throughout the game if others grasp the pattern  secondly  they will decrease the payouts of the other players.

It is the issue of trying to obtain the maximum possible outcome for every individual of the group. Based on the decision taken continually in a round robin fashioon check if the decision made fits the best possible outcome for verification

There was always a scenario that allowed everybody to make money. This scenario was easy to find out. After making a few mistakes  I deduced the best choice to pick and assumed others figured this out also.

If I was first I would look at how the last person would answer based on how I answered and worked backwards until I got back to my square and made it I would get the most points possible based on the thought that everyone would do the same. I was not first then I would see how the first person answered then look at what options that left the last person with and then work backwards until I reached my set of numbers.

I assumed that each player would choose an option that would maximize their profit.  If that was the case  you could figure out what each player would do. The choice of the first player affected the decision of the last player. If I knew what the first player did  I could figure out what everyone else would do. If I was the first player  I could decide which option would get me the most points.  This strategy seemed to work out for me in almost all the matches.

My decisions were based on predictions of others' decisions  and also based on the order of participation. |  | I kept in mind that our earnings were directly tied to our own decisions as well as others' decisions. Thus my biggest assumption was that others would make decisions in a way that maximizes their own overall payout. |  | The numbers also showed a pattern that we would not hurt ourselves by helping others so that observation also played into my decision-making.

When deciding which to pick  you start from the last person and decide what they're going to pick and then continue it backwards to see what everyone after you will pick  and then pick depending on that.

If you are the first or the second player then Choosing the box with a small sum payed off more and if your are a third or a fourth palyer  choosing the box with a higher total helped me more.... that's it !!
